    "body": "<!-- Before reporting: search existing issues and check the FAQ. -->\r\n\r\n- `nvim --version NVIM v0.5.0-dev`:\r\n- `vim -u DEFAULTS` (version: ) behaves differently? Yes (implicitly)\r\n- Operating system/version: macOS/linux\r\n- Terminal name/version: iTerm/alacritty\r\n- `$TERM`: xterm-256color\r\n\r\n### Steps to reproduce using `nvim -u NORC`\r\n\r\nAdd the following snippet to your init.lua:\r\n\r\n```lua\r\nfunction _G.statusline()\r\n    local filepath = '%f'\r\n    local align_section = '%='\r\n    local percentage_through_file = '%p%%'\r\n    return string.format(\r\n        '%s%s%s',\r\n        filepath,\r\n        align_section,\r\n        percentage_through_file\r\n    )\r\nend\r\n\r\nvim.cmd[[set statusline=%!v:lua.statusline()]]\r\n```\r\n\r\n### Actual behaviour\r\n\r\nThis is how smooth the scrolling is with the non-lua statusline.\r\n\r\nhttps://user-images.githubusercontent.com/13316262/106392709-e9e94800-63a7-11eb-8cb2-02bf7b32b45c.mp4\r\n\r\n\r\n### Expected behaviour\r\n\r\nOnce you scroll off buffer (flick the trackpad on a mac continuously), the lua statusline starts to lag, and continuous to lag/induce high cpu usages as you scroll back to the top. The hangs are most noticeable at the edge of the buffer. I'm wondering if we can just handle buffer scroll events when at the edge of the screen to avoid invoking the lua statusline.\r\n\r\ncc: @glepnir \r\n\r\n\r\nhttps://user-images.githubusercontent.com/13316262/106393001-4f8a0400-63a9-11eb-8987-807c7d924563.mp4\r\n\r\n\r\n",
